04817nam a2200673Ia 9780801470899DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014708997 a10.7591/97808014708992doi  a(DE-B1597)515861  a(OCoLC)872115350  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a958.72231 aReeves, Madeleine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBorder Work :bSpatial Lives of the State in Rural Central Asia /cMadeleine Reeves. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b31 halftones, 6 tables, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture and Society after Socialism00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Naming and Transliteration -- tIntroduction: On Border Work -- t1. Locations: Place and Displacement in Southern Ferghana -- t2. Delimitations: Ethno-Spatial Fixing in the Twentieth Century -- t3. Trajectories: Mobility and the Afterlives of Internationalism -- t4. Gaps: Working a “Chessboard” Border -- t5. Impersonations: Manning the Border, Enacting the State -- t6. Separations: Conflict and the Escalation of Force -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDrawing on extensive and carefully designed ethnographic fieldwork in the Ferghana Valley region, where the state borders of Kyrgyzstan, Tajikizstan and Uzbekistan intersect, Madeleine Reeves develops new ways of conceiving the state as a complex of relationships, and of state borders as socially constructed and in a constant state of flux. She explores the processes and relationships through which state borders are made, remade, interpreted and contested by a range of actors including politicians, state officials, border guards, farmers and people whose lives involve the crossing of the borders. In territory where international borders are not always clearly demarcated or consistently enforced, Reeves traces the ways in which states' attempts to establish their rule create new sources of conflict or insecurity for people pursuing their livelihoods in the area on the basis of older and less formal understandings of norms of access. As a result the book makes a major new and original contribution to scholarly work on Central Asia and more generally on the anthropology of border regions and the state as a social process. Moreover, the work as a whole is presented in a lively and accessible style. The individual lives whose tribulations and small triumphs Reeves so vividly documents, and the relationships she establishes with her subjects, are as revealing as they are engaging. Border Work is a well-deserved winner of this year’s Alexander Nove Prize.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBorderlandszFergana Valley. 0aEthnologyzFergana Valley. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  afieldwork, Ferghana Valley, ethnographic inquiry, remaking borders, state territoriality in Asia, territorial integrity, international borders, policing borders.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147089940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470899/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEB